subSection.paragraph:
Concerning phylogenetic studies in Elmidae , most of the previous analyses aimed to test the monophyly of Elmidae and to test the validity of the proposed subfamilies and tribes (Čiampor et al. 2016;
Kodada et al. 2016
;
Kundrata et al. 2016
;
Hayashi et al. 2019
;
Kobayashi et al. 2021
). Few studies have been done to clarify the relationships of species within genera of this family (
Linský et al. 2022
). The objective of this paper is to perform a systematic study of
Pilielmis
based on external and internal morphological characteristics of adults, improving the knowledge of this neotropical genus. These results will contribute to future systematic studies of the family and will expand knowledge about the biodiversity of aquatic insects in the Neotropical Region.

Type
material of 

Pilielmis

was analyzed from Natural History Museum, London, 
UK
(
NHMUK
) and Museu de Zoologia da Universidade de São Paulo (
MZSP
). Additional material was provided by loans from the following institutions: Coleção Entomológica Padre Jesus Santiago Moure, Universidade Federal do Paraná (
DZUP
); Setor de Entomologia da Coleção Zoológica da Universidade Federal de Mato Grosso (CEMT); Coleção de Invertebrados do Instituto Nacional de Pesquisas da Amazônia (
INPA
); and Snow Entomological Museum Collection of Natural History at the University of Kansas (
SEMC
).

Multi-layer photographs of the specimen were obtained using a Leica M165C stereomicroscope in conjunction with Leica DFC 420 image-capturing equipment and LED dome lighting for uniform and constant reflection of light on the specimens (
Kawada & Buffington 2016
) and an Olympus BX51 compound microscope in conjunction with an Olympus digital image-acquisition system (model DP 72 using the Cell D program). The final images were generated using Digital Leica Application Suite® v.3.7 and Helicon Focus® (6.7.1 Pro) software. Photographs were edited using Adobe Photoshop®.

The matrix was constructed using the WinClada program (
Nixon 2002
) and was exported to program TNT (
Goloboff & Catalano 2016
) where searches were conducted under equal and implied weights with different values of 
K
(from 1 to 10). In the implied weight strategy, the ideal weights of the characters are evaluated together with the tree search process (

Goloboff 
et al.
2008

). This last approach favors the phylogenetic signal of characters that have fewer homoplasies (
Schuh & Brower 2009
), resulting in a hypothesis that minimizes the total amount of homoplasy in the data and that supplies data with higher resolution.

